{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bb53d30c-2f33-4483-98c5-4aea09feeefc","content":"In .NET MAUI, `Application` no longer has `OnStart`/`OnSleep`/`OnResume`. Instead, use **Window lifecycle events**.\n\n**Option 1 — Subclass `Window`:**\n\n```csharp\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated()    { base.OnCreated(); /* was OnStart */ }\n    protected override void OnDeactivated(){ base.OnDeactivated(); /* was OnSleep */ }\n    protected override void OnResumed()    { base.OnResumed(); /* was OnResume */ }\n}\n```\n\nThen in your `App` class:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n    => new MyWindow(new AppShell());\n```\n\n**Option 2 — Inline events in `CreateWindow`:**\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = new Window(new AppShell());\n    window.Created     += (s, e) => { /* OnStart */ };\n    window.Deactivated += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep */ };\n    window.Resumed     += (s, e) => { /* OnResume */ };\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Mapping summary:**\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `Created` / `OnCreated()` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `Deactivated` / `OnDeactivated()` |\n| `OnResume()` | `Resumed` / `OnResumed()` |\n\nAdditional MAUI window events include `Activated`, `Stopped`, and `Destroying` for finer-grained control.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ad036e0e-0d7a-4612-b3ed-58fd4cf56ab4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` in your `Application` subclass.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the equivalent is to use the `Window` lifecycle events or the `ILifecycleBuilder` in `MauiProgram.cs`. The `Application` class in MAUI still has `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` — but the recommended approach is to use the Window lifecycle events or platform-specific lifecycle events.\n\n\nActually, I need to correct myself — the `Application` class in MAUI no longer has those lifecycle method overrides. Instead, you override `CreateWindow()` in your `Application` class to access the `Window` lifecycle events directly.\n\nThe mapping is straightforward: `OnStart` maps to `Window.Created`, `OnSleep` maps to either `Window.Deactivated` or `Window.Stopped`, and `OnResume` maps to `Window.Resumed` or `Window.Activated`. You can also use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs` for platform-specific handling.","outputTokens":929,"requestId":"B80B:18AE3E:13C5BE:19FC8A:69FFD859"},"id":"4b1080ae-ef66-48e0-a82a-b07b488f7954","timestamp":"2026-05-10T00:59:21.301Z","parentId":"14679960-5699-4bb8-a7af-198fccefbedf"}
